question_text:
A developer is debugging a CSS issue on a page that uses a CSS reset. They have the following HTML structure:

<div class="card">
  <h2 id="title" class="highlight">Hello</h2>
  <p class="highlight">World</p>
</div>

And the following CSS rules, loaded in this order:

1. reset.css (standard Eric Meyer reset)
2. styles.css with:

```css
.highlight {
  color: blue !important;
}

#title {
  color: green;
}

.card .highlight {
  color: red;
}

h2.highlight {
  color: orange;
}
```

What is the actual text color of the <h2> element after all styles are applied?

A developer is designing a page with a vertical rhythm grid of 20px per line. The base font size is 16px. They set the body's line-height to 1.25, so paragraph baselines are exactly every 20px. They then add an h2 element with the following CSS:

```css
h2 {
  font-size: 1.25rem;
  line-height: 1.2;
  margin-top: 1.5rem;
  margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
}
```

Assuming the root font-size is 16px, which of the following best describes the total height of the h2 from the top of its margin to the bottom of its margin?

