A developer is building a responsive card grid using CSS Grid. They want the grid to automatically adjust the number of columns based on available space without using media queries. They write the following CSS for the container:

.cards {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(220px, 1fr));
  gap: 1rem;
}

However, they notice that when there is only one card, it does not stretch to fill the full width of the container; instead it stays at 220px and leaves empty space. Which single change should they make to fix this?

A developer is building a responsive card gallery using CSS Grid. The HTML contains a container div with class 'gallery' and several child divs with class 'card'. Some cards also have class 'featured'. The developer writes the following CSS:

```css
.gallery {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
  gap: 16px;
  max-width: 1200px;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: 0 10px;
}

@media (min-width: 600px) {
  .featured {
    grid-column: span 2;
    grid-row: span 2;
  }
}
```

They notice that on a narrow screen (below 600px), the featured cards still appear larger than the other cards. What is the most likely cause?

