.featured { grid-column: span 2; grid-row: span 2; }

When the gallery container is 1000px wide, how many columns does the grid actually have, and what is the approximate width (in pixels) of each column track, assuming no extra spacing?

A developer is building a responsive card gallery. They want the grid to show cards in a single column on small phones (<400px), two columns on tablets (400–599px), and four columns on desktops (≥600px). Additionally, featured cards should be 2×2 on screens at least 400px wide, but should be 1×1 on smaller screens. They write the following CSS (mobile-first):

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  gap: 20px;
  margin: 20px auto;
  padding: 0 10px;
}

@media (min-width: 400px) {
  .container { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
  .featured  { grid-column: span 2; grid-row: span 2; }
}

@media (min-width: 600px) {
  .container {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    max-width: 960px;
  }
}
```

However, when testing on a tablet (450px wide), the featured cards appear as 1×1, not 2×2. What is the most likely cause?

A developer is designing a responsive card grid for a news website. She wants the grid to show 3 columns on large screens, 2 columns on medium screens, and 1 column on small screens. She writes the following CSS:

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr;
  gap: 1rem;
}
@media (max-width: 600px) {
