    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
  }
}
@media (max-width: 400px) {
  .container {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  }
}
```

She tests the page in a desktop browser and resizes the window. When the viewport is exactly 450px wide, how many columns does the grid display?

A developer is creating a responsive card grid using CSS Grid. They want the grid to display cards in a single column on small screens (≤400px), two columns between 400px and 600px, and four columns on screens 600px and wider. Featured cards should occupy 2x2 cells on screens 400px and wider, but on small screens they should be 1x1 like other cards. The developer writes the following CSS:

.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  gap: 20px;
}

@media (min-width: 400px) {
  .container {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
  }
